On February 11, 2020, the World Health Organization announced the official name of the disease – COVID-19.
WHO chief, Mr. Tedros Adan Gebreisus, explains: “CO” means “corona”, “VI” means “virus”, “D” means “disease”, and 19 – the year when the outbreak was first detected: December 31, 2019.
This name was chosen to avoid references to a specific geographic location (e.g. China), animal species or groups of people, as required by international naming recommendations aimed at preventing stigmatization of the virus RS2, a virus that causes COVID-19.
In public announcements, the WHO additionally uses the terms “covid-19 virus” and “covid-19 virus”.
